WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.262
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.070 --> 00:00:08.670
HARRY: I have to say I
personally believe that

00:00:08.670 --> 00:00:11.700
the timing cannot be any better
to have Congressman John Lewis

00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:12.300
here.

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:14.970
With tensions in the
country running high

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:16.640
and individuals
looking for guidance,

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:18.950
I believe Congressman John
Lewis is the perfect person

00:00:18.950 --> 00:00:20.210
to hear from at this time.

00:00:21.370 --> 00:00:24.770
Congressman Lewis served as
chair of the SNCC or Student

00:00:24.770 --> 00:00:27.400
Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:29.900
when he was a student at
Fisk, during the Civil Rights

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:32.240
Movement, and led
several marchings,

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:34.180
including the march
across the Edmund Pettus

00:00:34.180 --> 00:00:36.640
Bridge in Selma, Alabama,
which is known today

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:37.360
as Bloody Sunday.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:41.030
Serving in the United
States Congress,

00:00:41.030 --> 00:00:44.230
Congressman Lewis has
made his life-long goal

00:00:44.230 --> 00:00:47.940
to fight for civil and
human rights for all.

00:00:47.940 --> 00:00:50.010
A true champion
for us all, please

00:00:50.010 --> 00:00:52.095
welcome Congressman John Lewis.

00:00:52.095 --> 00:00:55.490
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:02.849 --> 00:01:04.390
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: Good morning.

00:01:06.050 --> 00:01:09.230
I'm delighted, very
happy, and very pleased

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:10.510
to be here at Google.

00:01:10.510 --> 00:01:11.620
Thank you so much.

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:12.420
You look good.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:16.780
Thank you, Harry, for those
kind words of introduction.

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:23.210
I'm happy and pleased to be
here with my co-author, Andrew

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:24.380
Aydin.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:30.610
It was his idea that got
me involved in this effort.

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:37.875
And we're so grateful that
you ally two guys that

00:01:37.875 --> 00:01:45.027
were born-- one born in
Atlanta, one in rural Alabama--

00:01:45.027 --> 00:01:45.985
to come from the South.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:49.780
Andrew would tell you that
I've been his congressperson

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:52.440
since he was only
three years old.

00:01:53.770 --> 00:01:58.220
So the people in Georgia
have been very good to me.

00:01:58.220 --> 00:02:01.430
Now I didn't grow up in
a big city like Atlanta.

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.620
I grew up in rural Alabama,
50 miles from Montgomery.

00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:08.889
My father was a sharecropper--
a tenant farmer.

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:13.500
But back in 1944 when I
was only four years old--

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:15.920
and I do remember
when I was four--

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:18.080
my father had saved $300.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:22.500
And with the $300 he
bought 110 acres of land.

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:25.225
My family still owns
this land today.

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:32.030
On this farm we raised a lot of
cotton and corn, peanuts, hogs,

00:02:32.030 --> 00:02:33.363
cows, and chickens.

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:37.270
I'll be very frank and
very honest with you,

00:02:37.270 --> 00:02:39.380
I didn't like working
out in the field.

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:42.100
I didn't like being
out in the hot sun.

00:02:42.100 --> 00:02:47.370
And I did everything possible
to escape working in the field.

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:49.340
I used to say to
my mother when I

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:52.830
would fall behind picking
cotton or gathering peanuts,

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:54.900
she would say, "Boy, catch up.

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:55.880
You're lagging behind.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:57.030
Catch up."

00:02:57.030 --> 00:02:59.280
And I would say,
"This is hard work."

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:02.505
And she would say, "Boy, hard
work never killed anybody.

00:03:02.505 --> 00:03:03.340
It won't kill you."

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:04.840
I said, well, it's
about to kill me.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:12.890
So during my early days
in school, especially

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:17.880
middle school, I would get
up early in the morning,

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:23.640
pack my book bag and hide
under the front porch

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:26.640
and wait until the
school bus come along

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:28.940
to get off to school.

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:32.730
Somehow I discovered that
education was important.

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:35.750
Now you heard me say
it earlier that we

00:03:35.750 --> 00:03:37.060
raised a lot of chickens.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:38.910
I know here at Google
you're just smart.

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:39.580
I can tell.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:41.580
But do you know anything
about raising chickens?

00:03:43.014 --> 00:03:45.180
You know something about
raising a chicken, brother?

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:45.920
AUDIENCE: Not much.

00:03:45.920 --> 00:03:47.090
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: Not much?

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:49.090
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
my grandmother's farm.

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:49.420
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS: OK.

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:51.175
Well, why don't we
compare notes here?

00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:55.360
AUDIENCE: We used to go out
and grab the eggs [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:56.503
We were kids.

00:03:56.503 --> 00:03:57.370
We'd just run in there and
grab what we would want.

00:03:57.370 --> 00:03:58.494
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS: Oh.

00:03:58.494 --> 00:04:00.840
Well, let's just
compare notes here.

00:04:00.840 --> 00:04:02.210
And let's have fun here.

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:04.710
Well, on the farm really
was my responsibility

00:04:04.710 --> 00:04:06.240
to care for the chickens.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:10.410
And I became very good, really
good at raising chickens.

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:14.100
When the setting hen was set,
I would take a fresh eggs,

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:17.370
mark them with a pencil, place
them under the setting hen,

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:21.060
and wait for three long weeks
for the chicks to hatch.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:22.680
You may be saying,
"Now John Lewis,

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.380
why did you mark those
fresh eggs with a pencil

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:27.600
before we placed them
under the setted hen?"

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:30.370
well, from time to
time, another hen

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:32.556
would get on that same nest.

00:04:32.556 --> 00:04:36.030
There would be some
more eggs-- fresh eggs.

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:39.430
Had to wait until the fresh eggs
for the eggs that were already

00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:40.623
under the setting hen.

00:04:40.623 --> 00:04:41.573
Do you follow me?

00:04:41.573 --> 00:04:42.280
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:42.660
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS: OK.

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:43.670
Good.

00:04:43.670 --> 00:04:45.372
When the little
chick would hatch,

00:04:45.372 --> 00:04:46.580
I would fool the setting hen.

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:48.038
I would cheat on
their setting hen.

00:04:48.038 --> 00:04:52.590
I would take these little chicks
and give them to another hen

00:04:52.590 --> 00:04:54.550
or put them in a
box with a lantern,

00:04:54.550 --> 00:04:56.155
raise them on their own.

00:04:56.155 --> 00:05:00.120
I was never quite
able to save $18.98

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:02.740
to order the most
inexpensive incubator

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:04.700
or hatcher from the
Sears and Roebuck Store.

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:08.750
Most of you in here are so
young you don't know anything

00:05:08.750 --> 00:05:10.980
about the Sears and
Roebuck catalog, do you?

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.490
You really do?

00:05:12.490 --> 00:05:13.020
Really?

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:13.950
That big book?

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:14.600
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:15.430
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: That thick book?

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:15.820
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:17.486
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: That heavy book?

00:05:17.486 --> 00:05:19.090
Some people called
it the wish book.

00:05:19.090 --> 00:05:20.020
I wish I had this.

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:21.470
I wish I had that.

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:24.030
So I just kept on
wishing as a little boy.

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:26.160
But as a little child, I
wanted to be a minister.

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:28.880
I wanted to preach the gospel.

00:05:29.990 --> 00:05:32.590
So from time to time to
helping my brothers and sisters

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:35.120
and cousins, we would
gather all of our chickens

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:37.875
together in the chicken
yard like you're

00:05:37.875 --> 00:05:40.310
gathered here in this room.

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:42.470
The chickens, along with
my brothers and sisters

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:46.050
and cousins, would make up the
audience, the congregation.

00:05:46.050 --> 00:05:47.717
And I would start
speaking or preaching.

00:05:47.717 --> 00:05:49.800
And when I look back on
it, some of these chickens

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:51.270
would bow their heads.

00:05:51.270 --> 00:05:53.720
Some of these chickens
would shake their heads.

00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:56.066
They never quite said Amen.

00:05:56.066 --> 00:05:58.607
But I'm convinced that some of
those chickens that I preached

00:05:58.607 --> 00:06:01.260
to in the '40s and
the '50s tended

00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:04.660
to listen to me much better
than some of my colleagues

00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:06.172
listen to me today
in the Congress.

00:06:06.172 --> 00:06:08.755
And some of those chickens were
just a little more productive.

00:06:10.450 --> 00:06:12.880
At least they produced eggs.

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:15.720
So that's the chicken story.

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:17.516
And that's enough of that story.

00:06:17.516 --> 00:06:19.515
But if we were to visit
the little town of Troy,

00:06:19.515 --> 00:06:24.285
or visit Montgomery, visit
Tuskegee, visit Birmingham,

00:06:24.285 --> 00:06:28.410
I saw those signs that said
white men, colored men,

00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:31.885
white women, colored women,
white waiting, colored waiting.

00:06:31.885 --> 00:06:33.900
And I didn't like it.

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:38.980
To go downtown to the theatre
on a Saturday afternoon,

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:41.900
all of us little black
children had to go upstairs

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:43.100
to the balcony.

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:45.300
All of the little white
children went downstairs

00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:46.890
to the first floor.

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:48.920
I would come home and
ask my mother, my father,

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:51.342
my grandparents, my
great-grandparents why.

00:06:51.342 --> 00:06:53.050
And they would say,
that's the way it is.

00:06:53.050 --> 00:06:53.970
Don't get in the way.

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:55.105
Don't get in trouble.

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:01.410
But one day I heard
about Rosa Parks,

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:03.130
15 years old in the 10th grade.

00:07:04.311 --> 00:07:06.310
I heard the words of
Martin Luther King, Junior,

00:07:06.310 --> 00:07:07.040
on our radio.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.440
The action of Rosa Parks,
the words and leadership

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:14.880
of Dr. King inspired
me to find a way

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:18.560
to get in the way to get in,
what I called, good trouble,

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:20.460
necessary trouble.

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:23.550
So in 1956, at the
age of 16, with some

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:25.564
of my brothers and
sisters and cousins,

00:07:25.564 --> 00:07:26.980
we went down to
the public library

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:31.760
in a little town
of Troy Alabama,

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:35.240
trying to get a library card
to check out some books.

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:37.150
And we were told
by the librarian

00:07:37.150 --> 00:07:39.625
that the library was for
whites only and not for colors.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:46.100
I never went back to that
library to that building

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:49.130
until July 5, 1998,
for a book signing

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:52.070
of my first book,
"Walking with to Wind."

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:54.337
And hundreds of black and
white citizens showed up,

00:07:54.337 --> 00:07:55.670
and they gave me a library card.

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:59.220
It says something about
the distance we have come

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:03.535
and the progress we have made in
laying down the burden of race.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:08.605
I don't know how many of you
have heard of Troy University.

00:08:09.730 --> 00:08:12.450
It was called Troy State
when I was growing up.

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:13.935
Only 10 miles from my home.

00:08:15.410 --> 00:08:20.330
Age of 17, 1957, I applied
to go to the school.

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:23.340
Submitted my application,
my high school transcript.

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:24.900
I never heard a word
from the school.

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:27.640
So I wrote a letter to Dr.
Martin Luther King, Junior.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:29.160
I didn't tell my
mother, my father,

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:31.960
any of my sisters or
brothers, any of my teachers.

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:34.330
I told Dr. King I
needed his help.

00:08:34.330 --> 00:08:37.120
Martin Luther King,
Junior, wrote me back,

00:08:37.120 --> 00:08:39.289
sent me a round trip
Greyhound bus ticket,

00:08:39.289 --> 00:08:42.580
and invited me to come to
Montgomery to meet with him.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:44.149
In the meantime, I
had been accepted

00:08:44.149 --> 00:08:45.940
at a little school in
Nashville, Tennessee.

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:50.650
So in September,
1957, an uncle of mine

00:08:50.650 --> 00:08:53.845
gave me a $100 bill-- more
money than I ever had.

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:57.280
Gave me one of these
big foot-lockers,

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:01.570
these up-right trunks
that you can open up then

00:09:01.570 --> 00:09:04.270
bring it back together,
that had to drawers

00:09:04.270 --> 00:09:05.977
that you could put things in.

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:10.040
And then a compartment
where you can hang-- Andy,

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:11.850
you remember that foot locker?

00:09:11.850 --> 00:09:13.940
I still have that foot locker.

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:16.110
It's big and old.

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:21.575
But I boarded that
bus-- a Greyhound bus.

00:09:21.575 --> 00:09:27.850
And I put everything that
I own in that foot locker,

00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:32.040
except those chickens, and went
off to school to Nashville.

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:34.210
And after being in
Nashville for a few weeks,

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:36.609
I told one of my
teachers that I'd

00:09:36.609 --> 00:09:38.900
been in contact with Doctor
Martin Luther King, Junior.

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:41.960
This teacher knew Doctor King.

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:45.095
Both had studied at Morehouse
College, the same school

00:09:45.095 --> 00:09:46.590
that Harry Johnson studied.

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:53.100
And he informed Dr. King
that I was in Nashville.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:54.870
Martin Luther King,
Junior, got in touch

00:09:54.870 --> 00:09:57.460
and suggested when I went
home for Spring Break

00:09:57.460 --> 00:09:59.480
to come and see him.

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:04.240
So in March of 1958-- by
this time I'm 18 years old--

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:06.560
my father drove me to the
Greyhound bus station.

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:08.615
I boarded the bus and
traveled to Montgomery.

00:10:10.550 --> 00:10:12.970
And a young lawyer--
I'd never seen a lawyer

00:10:12.970 --> 00:10:17.680
before-- a young man by
the name of Fred Gray,

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:19.780
who had been a lawyer
for Rosa Parks,

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:22.295
for Dr. King, and the
Montgomery Movement,

00:10:22.295 --> 00:10:26.480
and became our lawyer during
the freedom rides and the march

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:30.510
from Selma to Montgomery,
met me at the bus station

00:10:30.510 --> 00:10:32.210
and drove me to the
First Baptist Church

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.850
in downtown Montgomery,
pastored by the Reverend Ralph

00:10:34.850 --> 00:10:38.656
Abernathy, and then ushered me
into the office of the church.

00:10:38.656 --> 00:10:40.030
I saw Martin Luther
King, Junior,

00:10:40.030 --> 00:10:42.640
and Ralph Abernathy
standing behind a desk.

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:44.040
I was so scared.

00:10:44.040 --> 00:10:46.050
I didn't know to
say or what to do.

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:48.060
And Dr. King said, "Are
you the boy from Troy?

00:10:49.570 --> 00:10:51.810
Are you John Lewis?"

00:10:51.810 --> 00:10:55.360
And I said, "Dr. King,
I am John Robert Lewis."

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:57.060
I gave my whole name.

00:10:57.060 --> 00:10:59.630
And that was the beginning
of my involvement

00:10:59.630 --> 00:11:01.325
with Martin Luther King, Junior.

00:11:01.325 --> 00:11:04.680
And it changed my life forever,
and I have not looked back.

00:11:05.961 --> 00:11:08.500
I had a discussion
with my parents.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:11.015
They were so frightened
when I got back home.

00:11:11.015 --> 00:11:13.240
They thought our
house would be bombed,

00:11:13.240 --> 00:11:14.635
that we would lose the land.

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:18.050
And so I continued to
study in Nashville.

00:11:18.050 --> 00:11:20.400
So it was in Nashville
that we started

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:22.606
studying the way of
peace, the way of love,

00:11:22.606 --> 00:11:23.606
the way of non-violence.

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:27.100
That we start sitting
in, be sitting there

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:30.020
in an orderly, peaceful,
nonviolent fashion,

00:11:30.020 --> 00:11:31.690
waiting to be
served, and someone

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:35.540
would come up and spit on us
or put lighted cigarettes out

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:38.595
in our hair or down our
backs, pour hot water,

00:11:38.595 --> 00:11:41.180
hot coffee, hot chocolate on us.

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:46.120
We just stayed there,
looking straight ahead.

00:11:47.750 --> 00:11:51.600
And Andrew Aydin will tell
you that the first time

00:11:51.600 --> 00:11:57.590
I was arrested on February
27, 1960, just turned 20.

00:11:57.590 --> 00:12:01.150
He discovered, a few
weeks ago, a photograph

00:12:01.150 --> 00:12:02.030
of my first arrest.

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:06.920
In Nashville during the '60s and
many other parts of the South,

00:12:06.920 --> 00:12:10.150
we wanted to sort of dress
up, put on our Sunday

00:12:10.150 --> 00:12:13.110
best when we went to
participate in a protest.

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:18.252
I didn't have much or any money.

00:12:18.252 --> 00:12:19.085
I wanted a new suit.

00:12:21.250 --> 00:12:26.170
So I went to used men's
store in downtown Nashville,

00:12:26.170 --> 00:12:27.070
and I bought a suit.

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:32.460
Now to tell you how much
a suit costs, it was $5.

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:35.194
I wish I still had it.

00:12:35.194 --> 00:12:36.735
I don't know what
I would do with it.

00:12:37.930 --> 00:12:39.900
I just don't know what
I would do with it.

00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:41.770
But maybe I would give
it to some museum.

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:45.450
Maybe the Smithsonian
or someplace.

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:46.980
I don't know.

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:47.810
But I looked good.

00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:50.650
If you come to Washington,
we have a photograph

00:12:50.650 --> 00:12:54.060
of that suit and I
me being arrested.

00:12:54.060 --> 00:12:55.760
And you can see it.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:59.150
So I would invite
any of you who want

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:01.270
to be in Washington
any time to come

00:13:01.270 --> 00:13:03.800
by my congressional office.

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:05.520
It looks like a working museum.

00:13:07.930 --> 00:13:09.335
But we didn't give up.

00:13:09.335 --> 00:13:10.620
We didn't give in.

00:13:11.730 --> 00:13:13.430
We kept the faith.

00:13:13.430 --> 00:13:15.436
We kept our eyes on the prize.

00:13:15.436 --> 00:13:16.435
We didn't become bitter.

00:13:16.435 --> 00:13:18.440
We didn't become hostile.

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:22.390
Many of us accepted the way
of peace, the way of love,

00:13:22.390 --> 00:13:26.860
the way of non-violence as a
way of life, as a way of living.

00:13:26.860 --> 00:13:32.510
So during the '60s I was
arrested 40 times, left beaten.

00:13:32.510 --> 00:13:36.820
Just think, 1961, the same year
that President Barack Obama was

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:39.870
born, black people
and white people

00:13:39.870 --> 00:13:44.810
couldn't leave together
on a bus or train

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:49.050
with white people seated
together traveling to the south

00:13:49.050 --> 00:13:52.080
to Virginia through
North Carolina,

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:55.217
through South Carolina, through
Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi,

00:13:55.217 --> 00:13:56.300
on our way to New Orleans.

00:13:57.980 --> 00:14:00.491
Many people came from
the state of California

00:14:00.491 --> 00:14:01.490
during the freedom riot.

00:14:04.569 --> 00:14:05.360
They came to Selma.

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:11.755
50 years ago this summer,
many came to Mississippi.

00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:20.290
I'm going to cut it short and
leave some time for Andrew.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:26.430
But during the
March on Washington,

00:14:26.430 --> 00:14:27.580
I was the youngest speaker.

00:14:28.630 --> 00:14:29.490
I spoke number six.

00:14:32.150 --> 00:14:33.470
Dr. King spoke number 10.

00:14:33.470 --> 00:14:35.130
There was 10 of us.

00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:36.980
Out of the 10 people
that spoke that day,

00:14:36.980 --> 00:14:38.230
I'm the only one still around.

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:42.230
When the March on
Washington was over,

00:14:42.230 --> 00:14:45.790
President Kennedy invited us all
back down to the White House.

00:14:45.790 --> 00:14:49.120
He stood in the door of the Oval
Office greeting each one of us.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:51.962
And he kept saying he was
beaming like a proud father.

00:14:51.962 --> 00:14:53.420
He kept saying,
you did a good job.

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:54.215
You did a good job.

00:14:55.410 --> 00:14:58.310
And when he got to Dr. Martin
Luther King, Junior, he said,

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:01.429
"And you had a dream."
it was my last time

00:15:01.429 --> 00:15:02.470
seeing President Kennedy.

00:15:04.890 --> 00:15:09.000
Those of us that organized
the march to leadership,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.395
we emerged black
and white as a circa

00:15:12.395 --> 00:15:16.215
of trust, a band of
brothers and sisters.

00:15:18.090 --> 00:15:20.520
But 18 days after the
March on Washington

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:22.900
was a terrible bombing of
the church in Birmingham

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:26.970
where four little girls were
killed on a Sunday morning

00:15:26.970 --> 00:15:28.580
because of what happened.

00:15:28.580 --> 00:15:31.620
We intensified our efforts
to gain the right to vote.

00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:36.340
Just think, in a state
like Mississippi in 1964,

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:38.610
the state had a black
voting age population

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:42.680
of more than 450,000,
and only about 16,000

00:15:42.680 --> 00:15:43.580
registered to vote.

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.080
And there was one county in
a state of Alabama-- Lowndes

00:15:47.080 --> 00:15:47.700
County.

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:51.230
Between Selma and Montgomery--
the county was more than 80%

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:54.630
African American, but there
was not a single registered

00:15:54.630 --> 00:15:56.540
African American
voter in the county.

00:15:58.510 --> 00:16:03.000
In some parts of the South,
in Alabama and Mississippi,

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
people were asked to count
the number of bubbles

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.470
in a bar of soap, count the
number of jelly beans in a jar.

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:14.200
The [INAUDIBLE] section
of the Constitution

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:17.390
of Mississippi or the state of
Alabama or the US Constitution.

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:22.730
People were beaten, people were
arrested, people were jailed.

00:16:22.730 --> 00:16:26.860
Three young men-- Andy Goodman,
Mickey Schwerner and James

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:31.570
Chaney-- went out on a summer
night of June 21, 1964,

00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:35.782
to investigate the burning of
an African American church,

00:16:35.782 --> 00:16:37.990
the church which would be
used for voter registration

00:16:37.990 --> 00:16:39.200
workshop.

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:43.760
These three young men were
detained by the sheriff,

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:47.890
arrested, taken to jail,
and later that evening

00:16:47.890 --> 00:16:51.940
taken out of jail,
turned over to that Klan

00:16:51.940 --> 00:16:55.077
where they were beaten,
shot, and killed.

00:16:55.077 --> 00:16:57.660
These three young men didn't die
in the Middle East or Eastern

00:16:57.660 --> 00:16:58.505
Europe.

00:16:58.505 --> 00:17:03.529
They didn't die in Vietnam,
Central South America.

00:17:03.529 --> 00:17:05.195
They died right here
in our own country.

00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:11.800
And that's why I say to young
people today and those of us

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:14.210
not so young, the
vote is precious.

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:18.819
And a democracy such as
ours is almost sacred.

00:17:19.849 --> 00:17:21.940
And that's why we
all must participate

00:17:21.940 --> 00:17:23.004
in the political process.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:30.530
President Lyndon Johnson signed
the Civil Rights Act of '64

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:31.490
on July 2.

00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:38.270
Dr. King received the Nobel
Peace Prize in December, 1964.

00:17:38.270 --> 00:17:42.010
He come back from Europe, hold
a meeting at the White House

00:17:42.010 --> 00:17:46.120
and said to President Johnson,
we need a Voter Rights Act.

00:17:46.120 --> 00:17:47.749
President Johnson
said, I cannot do it.

00:17:47.749 --> 00:17:49.540
We don't have of the
votes in the Congress.

00:17:50.857 --> 00:17:51.815
I cannot get it passed.

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:58.670
Dr. King made a
decision to go to Selma

00:17:58.670 --> 00:18:02.100
and join the students in the
Student Nonviolent Coordinating

00:18:02.100 --> 00:18:02.600
Committee.

00:18:03.640 --> 00:18:07.300
In Selma, only 2.1% of
blacks of voting age

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:09.050
were registered to vote.

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:10.730
You could only
attempt to register

00:18:10.730 --> 00:18:13.282
to vote on the first and
third Mondays of each month,

00:18:13.282 --> 00:18:14.990
and you had to go down
to the courthouse.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:20.410
And in Selma you had a sheriff
who was a very big man, tall,

00:18:20.410 --> 00:18:21.410
he was mean.

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:22.200
He got up mean.

00:18:23.340 --> 00:18:25.890
He would sleep mean
and dream mean.

00:18:25.890 --> 00:18:26.800
He was just mean.

00:18:28.010 --> 00:18:30.860
He work a gun on one side, a
night stick on the other side,

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:33.730
and he carried an electric
cow prodder in this hand.

00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:35.185
And he didn't use it on cows.

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:39.840
Many of us were arrested
by him for standing in line

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:42.460
and encouraging people to
stay in line and attempt

00:18:42.460 --> 00:18:45.510
to get their literacy test
or attempt to pass their test

00:18:45.510 --> 00:18:47.260
to become a registered voter.

00:18:47.260 --> 00:18:52.900
But on March 7, 1965,
600 of us attempted

00:18:52.900 --> 00:18:55.860
to walk from Selma to
Montgomery, Alabama,

00:18:55.860 --> 00:18:59.410
50 miles away, to dramatize
to the state of Alabama,

00:18:59.410 --> 00:19:02.280
to the nation, and to the
world, that people wanted

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:04.175
to participate in a
democratic process.

00:19:07.550 --> 00:19:09.020
We were orderly.

00:19:09.020 --> 00:19:11.620
I was wearing a
backpack before it

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:14.030
became fashionable
to wear backpacks.

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:15.990
And in this backpack
I had two books.

00:19:15.990 --> 00:19:18.570
I wanted to have
something to read in jail.

00:19:18.570 --> 00:19:20.380
I had one apple and one orange.

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:22.150
I wanted to have
something to eat.

00:19:22.150 --> 00:19:24.702
Now one apple and one orange
wouldn't last that long.

00:19:24.702 --> 00:19:26.160
And since I was
going to be in jail

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:29.660
with my friends and my
colleagues and neighbors,

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:31.710
I wanted to be able
to brush my teeth, so

00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:33.035
toothpaste and toothbrush.

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:37.210
We get to the highest point
on the Edmund Pettus Bridge,

00:19:37.210 --> 00:19:38.830
crossing the Alabama River.

00:19:38.830 --> 00:19:41.980
Down below we saw a sea of
blue Alabama State Troopers.

00:19:44.375 --> 00:19:45.125
Continued to walk.

00:19:46.860 --> 00:19:49.140
We came within hearing
distance of the state troopers.

00:19:50.470 --> 00:19:54.120
A major spoke up and said, "I'm
Major John Cloud of the Alabama

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:54.745
State Troopers.

00:19:54.745 --> 00:19:56.322
This is an unlawful march.

00:19:56.322 --> 00:19:57.780
It will not be
allowed to continue.

00:19:57.780 --> 00:20:00.600
I give you three minutes
to disperse and return

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:03.280
to your homes or
to your church."

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:06.230
A young man from Dr.
King's organization

00:20:06.230 --> 00:20:09.530
leading the march with
me said, "Major, give us

00:20:09.530 --> 00:20:11.350
a moment to kneel and pray."

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:13.725
And the major said,
"Troopers, advance."

00:20:13.725 --> 00:20:16.195
You saw these guys putting
on their gas masks.

00:20:17.330 --> 00:20:20.530
They came toward us, beating
us with night sticks and bull

00:20:20.530 --> 00:20:24.167
whips, trampling us with horses
and releasing the tear gas.

00:20:24.167 --> 00:20:25.750
I was the first
person to be attacked.

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:29.690
Hit in the head by a state
trooper with a night stick,

00:20:29.690 --> 00:20:33.464
had a concussion at the bridge,
I thought it was going to die.

00:20:33.464 --> 00:20:34.380
I thought I saw death.

00:20:35.450 --> 00:20:37.930
Next year will be
the 50th anniversary

00:20:37.930 --> 00:20:40.060
of the march from
Selma to Montgomery.

00:20:40.060 --> 00:20:41.640
Finally, we made it there.

00:20:42.870 --> 00:20:47.590
The next day, Dr. King
came and said to me,

00:20:47.590 --> 00:20:49.830
"We'll make it from
Selma to Montgomery.

00:20:49.830 --> 00:20:51.695
The Voting Rights
Act will be passed."

00:20:51.695 --> 00:20:54.700
He issued a call for religious
leaders to come to Selma.

00:20:55.840 --> 00:20:59.760
On the following Tuesday, more
than 1,000 ministers, priests,

00:20:59.760 --> 00:21:03.075
rabbis, and nuns came and
walked across that bridge.

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:06.590
President Johnson made one of
the most meaningful speeches

00:21:06.590 --> 00:21:09.940
that any American president
had made in modern time

00:21:09.940 --> 00:21:13.450
on the whole question of
Civil Rights or voting rights.

00:21:13.450 --> 00:21:16.450
And the near the end
of that speech after he

00:21:16.450 --> 00:21:18.720
had introduced the
Voting Rights Act,

00:21:18.720 --> 00:21:21.430
he used the theme song to
the Civil Rights Movement

00:21:21.430 --> 00:21:24.390
and he said, "And
we shall overcome."

00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:27.000
I was sitting next to
Martin Luther King, Junior,

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.650
in a home of a local family
there in Selma, Alabama,

00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:32.990
as we witnessed and
listened to Lyndon Johnson.

00:21:32.990 --> 00:21:36.090
And when President Johnson
said, we shall overcome,

00:21:36.090 --> 00:21:37.515
I looked at Dr. King.

00:21:37.515 --> 00:21:40.420
And tears came down this face.

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:42.097
And we all cried
a little to hear

00:21:42.097 --> 00:21:44.555
the President of the United
States state we shall overcome.

00:21:46.110 --> 00:21:50.260
So because of the action
and the marching feet

00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:53.445
of so many people, America's
a different America.

00:21:53.445 --> 00:21:55.050
It's a better America.

00:21:55.050 --> 00:21:56.360
We're not there yet.

00:21:56.360 --> 00:21:58.450
We still have a distance to go.

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:00.665
But in the final
analysis, we all

00:22:00.665 --> 00:22:04.770
must keep in mind that we're
one people, we're one family,

00:22:04.770 --> 00:22:06.200
we're one house.

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:09.810
It doesn't matter whether
we're black or white or Latino,

00:22:09.810 --> 00:22:12.230
Asian American or
Native American.

00:22:12.230 --> 00:22:14.896
It doesn't matter whether
we're straight or gay,

00:22:14.896 --> 00:22:17.600
we're all a member
of the human family.

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:20.015
We must look out for each
other and care for each other.

00:22:20.015 --> 00:22:25.060
In closing I say thank you,
Google-- the Google family--

00:22:25.060 --> 00:22:28.750
for all that you do to
bring this little spaceship,

00:22:28.750 --> 00:22:32.190
the members of the human
race, a little closer

00:22:32.190 --> 00:22:35.620
together as one
people and one family.

00:22:35.620 --> 00:22:43.310
And now let me pause and yield
to my friend, my brother,

00:22:43.310 --> 00:22:46.000
and someone acts
almost like he's

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.930
my son, Andrew Aydin,
the co-author on "March."

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:52.742
[APPLAUSE]

00:23:05.589 --> 00:23:07.130
ANDREW AYDIN: How
do you follow that?

00:23:12.084 --> 00:23:14.250
Perhaps some of you are
asking, why would John Lewis

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:15.240
write a graphic novel?

00:23:16.590 --> 00:23:18.090
And it's a fair question.

00:23:20.140 --> 00:23:21.930
But what I hope to
tell you real quickly

00:23:21.930 --> 00:23:25.310
is a story about how Dr. King,
himself, used one as well.

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:29.010
When I was on the
campaign in 2008,

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:31.160
I was going to a comic
book convention afterwards.

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:32.980
And I admitted it.

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:34.865
I said it out loud
to my colleagues,

00:23:34.865 --> 00:23:36.790
and they laughed at me.

00:23:36.790 --> 00:23:38.369
And Congressman
said, "Don't laugh.

00:23:38.369 --> 00:23:40.160
There was a comic book
during the Movement,

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:42.462
and it was incredibly
influential."

00:23:42.462 --> 00:23:44.420
And right off the bat it
started a conversation

00:23:44.420 --> 00:23:47.440
with me wondering why doesn't
John Lewis write a comic book?

00:23:47.440 --> 00:23:50.550
Why doesn't he tell
his story because he's

00:23:50.550 --> 00:23:53.180
lived so much of the seminal
moments of the Movement.

00:23:54.950 --> 00:23:57.400
If they used a comic book
once to help teach people

00:23:57.400 --> 00:23:59.625
about nonviolence, why
can't we do it again?

00:23:59.625 --> 00:24:02.380
And at the same time I
went back to Washington

00:24:02.380 --> 00:24:04.480
after this campaign was over.

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:09.080
I went to grad school
at night and started

00:24:09.080 --> 00:24:10.800
working on my graduate thesis.

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:12.950
And I decided to write
about Martin Luther

00:24:12.950 --> 00:24:15.540
King and the Montgomery
story-- this comic book.

00:24:19.510 --> 00:24:21.860
You might not know
it, because it

00:24:21.860 --> 00:24:23.780
is sort of one of those
under-told stories,

00:24:23.780 --> 00:24:26.255
but what we found out
was Dr. King edited it,

00:24:26.255 --> 00:24:28.791
it was endorsed by
A. Philip Randolph,

00:24:28.791 --> 00:24:30.290
and it was used
throughout the South

00:24:30.290 --> 00:24:32.810
by people like Jim
Lawson, Congressman Lewis'

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:35.889
mentor in Nashville, to
educate and, in fact,

00:24:35.889 --> 00:24:37.430
inspire some of the
earliest sit-ins.

00:24:39.930 --> 00:24:42.654
And so, it seemed almost
self-evident to me

00:24:42.654 --> 00:24:44.070
that perhaps we
could do it again.

00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:48.340
That we're facing
the same struggles--

00:24:48.340 --> 00:24:53.510
we see police brutality,
attacks on voting rights--

00:24:53.510 --> 00:24:56.300
how do we get a young
activist generation to step up

00:24:56.300 --> 00:24:59.000
again and fight
that fight with us?

00:24:59.877 --> 00:25:01.710
There's three things
you need in a movement.

00:25:03.210 --> 00:25:05.395
You need financing.

00:25:06.720 --> 00:25:09.240
You need adequate
tools and strategy.

00:25:10.590 --> 00:25:12.790
And you need activists
willing to give everything

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:13.470
that they can.

00:25:15.050 --> 00:25:16.920
And it has to be young people.

00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:18.040
They're the most free.

00:25:18.040 --> 00:25:19.165
They're the most liberated.

00:25:19.937 --> 00:25:21.020
They don't have mortgages.

00:25:21.020 --> 00:25:21.890
They don't have families.

00:25:21.890 --> 00:25:22.765
They don't have kids.

00:25:23.487 --> 00:25:25.320
They're the only ones
who can put themselves

00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:29.940
on the line as young radicals,
as they called the Congressman,

00:25:29.940 --> 00:25:32.870
for believing simply that a
sixth grade education should

00:25:32.870 --> 00:25:35.350
not be a requirement to
vote, as was proposed

00:25:35.350 --> 00:25:36.780
in the original
Civil Rights Bill.

00:25:39.950 --> 00:25:42.470
So, when I asked the
Congressman why don't you

00:25:42.470 --> 00:25:44.550
write a comic book, he
sort of looked at me

00:25:44.550 --> 00:25:46.246
and said, you know, oh.

00:25:46.246 --> 00:25:47.465
Maybe a nod.

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:51.500
But I kept asking and asking.

00:25:52.670 --> 00:25:53.670
And finally he said, OK.

00:25:53.670 --> 00:25:56.250
Let's do it, but only
if you write it with me.

00:25:57.596 --> 00:25:59.470
And it was one of those
challenges in my life

00:25:59.470 --> 00:26:01.660
that you rarely get.

00:26:01.660 --> 00:26:04.020
And if you let it
go, you've missed

00:26:04.020 --> 00:26:06.230
this incredible opportunity.

00:26:06.230 --> 00:26:09.592
But more importantly, perhaps
missed your own life's mission.

00:26:09.592 --> 00:26:10.550
And I couldn't do that.

00:26:10.550 --> 00:26:11.390
I grabbed onto it.

00:26:11.390 --> 00:26:13.360
And for five years--
Harry knows this.

00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:15.570
He saw me at night and
on weekends-- worrying

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:17.160
about that dad gum comic book.

00:26:18.537 --> 00:26:20.370
Because that's when we
had a day job, and so

00:26:20.370 --> 00:26:22.220
we were doing it at
night, on the phone,

00:26:22.220 --> 00:26:23.390
when we could get together.

00:26:25.790 --> 00:26:27.690
And we put our heart
and soul into it.

00:26:29.130 --> 00:26:33.040
It grew from one book to three,
because what do you leave out?

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:35.010
Whose story don't you tell?

00:26:35.010 --> 00:26:37.930
What key part of the
Civil Rights Movement

00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:38.900
is not worth telling?

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:44.990
And low and behold,
it started to seem

00:26:44.990 --> 00:26:46.344
like it was going to work.

00:26:46.344 --> 00:26:48.260
There were some surreal
moments along the way.

00:26:49.090 --> 00:26:51.590
One of them was I was on the
pilgrimage with the Congressman

00:26:51.590 --> 00:26:53.280
and I get on an
elevator, and there

00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:56.540
is Ethel Kennedy,
Robert Kennedy's widow,

00:26:56.540 --> 00:26:58.620
and John Seigenthaler,
who was Robert Kennedy's

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:00.237
aid during the Freedom
Rides and later

00:27:00.237 --> 00:27:01.945
the publisher of the
National Tennessean.

00:27:03.651 --> 00:27:04.864
And this is a theme.

00:27:04.864 --> 00:27:06.780
Again, I was young and
didn't know any better.

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:08.200
And so I asked.

00:27:08.200 --> 00:27:10.240
I said, I'm sorry to
bother you, but I just

00:27:10.240 --> 00:27:12.120
thought you'd want to know.

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:13.920
You're in a comic book
that I'm working on

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:14.795
with the Congressman.

00:27:16.050 --> 00:27:18.550
And Ethel Kennedy looked up at
me with these beautiful eyes

00:27:18.550 --> 00:27:21.380
and she just said,
"That's nice dear."

00:27:23.530 --> 00:27:26.990
So it was a tremendous thrill
when she called me about

00:27:26.990 --> 00:27:30.100
a year-and-a-half later
to say that "March"

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:32.740
book one would be the first
graphic novel ever to receive

00:27:32.740 --> 00:27:34.868
the Robert F Kennedy Book Award.

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:40.860
The moment, though,
I think when we

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:42.360
knew that this book
was really going

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:44.940
to be something special,
that it was actually

00:27:44.940 --> 00:27:48.510
going to work as a
tool for nonviolence

00:27:48.510 --> 00:27:51.430
and teaching another
generation was right

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:53.185
after we had the first
advance copies out.

00:27:54.220 --> 00:27:55.865
And I got a phone
call from a reporter.

00:27:56.851 --> 00:27:58.350
And he said I don't
usually do this,

00:27:58.350 --> 00:28:00.224
but I gave your book to
my nine-year-old son.

00:28:02.210 --> 00:28:04.567
And he's gone and put
on his Sunday suit,

00:28:04.567 --> 00:28:06.150
and now he's marching
around my house,

00:28:06.150 --> 00:28:07.610
demanding equality for everyone.

00:28:11.370 --> 00:28:13.470
Imagine if we could develop
a social consciousness

00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:14.886
in every nine-year-old
in America.

00:28:15.697 --> 00:28:17.530
What that would mean
for the next generation

00:28:17.530 --> 00:28:19.980
and what they would be
capable of doing, particularly

00:28:19.980 --> 00:28:23.350
if they were well-informed and
capable of using nonviolence

00:28:23.350 --> 00:28:25.400
in a disciplined
and orderly way.

00:28:25.400 --> 00:28:26.590
It's not just a philosophy.

00:28:26.590 --> 00:28:27.820
It's a tactic.

00:28:27.820 --> 00:28:30.155
And it's the only tactic
that truly will work.

00:28:33.620 --> 00:28:37.385
There was a reviewer
in France, and he

00:28:37.385 --> 00:28:39.220
used a phrase that
stuck with me.

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:45.265
He called it a weapon
of mass instruction.

00:28:49.234 --> 00:28:51.150
I never thought I would
be able to participate

00:28:51.150 --> 00:28:52.530
in creating something like that.

00:28:54.150 --> 00:28:57.136
But as we stand here now, about
13 months after it's released,

00:28:57.136 --> 00:28:58.510
the Washington
Post said it needs

00:28:58.510 --> 00:29:00.700
to be in every school
and library in America.

00:29:00.700 --> 00:29:03.050
NPR called it the next mouse.

00:29:03.050 --> 00:29:04.900
I called it beginner's luck.

00:29:07.426 --> 00:29:09.550
But it's because John Lewis'
story is so important.

00:29:11.412 --> 00:29:12.870
We see a generation
of young people

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:16.279
who don't know how to make
a difference sometimes,

00:29:16.279 --> 00:29:18.070
and particularly, with
all the resources we

00:29:18.070 --> 00:29:18.944
have with technology.

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:22.130
And we have to teach
them that nonviolence

00:29:22.130 --> 00:29:24.880
is the viable path forward.

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:30.242
I handle tech and telecom issues
in the congressman's office.

00:29:30.242 --> 00:29:32.700
And I also do his social media,
so I'm basically head nerd.

00:29:34.110 --> 00:29:35.500
And we're taking over the world.

00:29:35.500 --> 00:29:38.647
We have to admit now, we
almost have a hegemonic state.

00:29:38.647 --> 00:29:39.230
We're winning.

00:29:40.570 --> 00:29:42.380
But what I'm constantly
struggling with

00:29:42.380 --> 00:29:44.795
is the concept of
what would Dr. King

00:29:44.795 --> 00:29:47.335
or what would Gandhi have
done with these tools?

00:29:50.540 --> 00:29:51.860
It's a profound question.

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:56.205
And more importantly,
where is Google Organize?

00:29:57.270 --> 00:29:58.540
Where is a Google March?

00:30:01.230 --> 00:30:04.190
These technologies allow
people to be reached

00:30:04.190 --> 00:30:07.656
in such a broad way that
we've never had access before,

00:30:07.656 --> 00:30:09.780
and we're just starting to
see the beginning of it.

00:30:09.780 --> 00:30:11.655
You think about the
Tahrir Square Revolution.

00:30:12.710 --> 00:30:14.160
I'll draw this
connection for you.

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:16.721
It was Facebook that
helped them organize,

00:30:16.721 --> 00:30:18.970
but it was Martin Luther
King and the Montgomery story

00:30:18.970 --> 00:30:22.269
translated into Arabic that was
distributed just before they

00:30:22.269 --> 00:30:23.060
started organizing.

00:30:25.050 --> 00:30:26.470
So we can connect those pieces.

00:30:26.470 --> 00:30:28.670
If we can get them
to ask the questions

00:30:28.670 --> 00:30:31.920
and then use the
technology to organize,

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:35.070
the potential to remake
our society is limitless.

00:30:35.070 --> 00:30:37.714
And I think that's exactly
what you're trying to do here.

00:30:37.714 --> 00:30:39.880
So that's why I appreciate
you having us and letting

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:41.550
us bring "March."

00:30:41.550 --> 00:30:43.920
Because we want to
be that first step,

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:47.080
so that the young people
ask the questions,

00:30:47.080 --> 00:30:49.390
and then they use your
tools to make it a reality.

00:30:51.182 --> 00:30:51.890
So I'll be brief.

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:53.723
I just thank you guys
so much for having me.

00:30:53.723 --> 00:30:54.960
This is a real thrill.

00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:57.410
I was in college and
started a television station

00:30:57.410 --> 00:31:00.770
using Google Video
back in the day.

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:06.830
So it's a real honor to be here.

00:31:06.830 --> 00:31:08.209
Thank you guys so much.

00:31:08.209 --> 00:31:11.702
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:13.604 --> 00:31:15.020
AUDIENCE: Congressman,
what really

00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:18.970
struck me was the story that
you mentioned about your father

00:31:18.970 --> 00:31:22.640
having been a tenant farmer and
buying the land for $300 that's

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:24.460
still in your family today.

00:31:24.460 --> 00:31:25.960
And when I think
about that, I think

00:31:25.960 --> 00:31:28.190
about the incredible
upward mobility

00:31:28.190 --> 00:31:30.430
that's afforded to
people and to families

00:31:30.430 --> 00:31:34.540
by being able to go
from working just

00:31:34.540 --> 00:31:37.097
for their monthly income to
actually generating value

00:31:37.097 --> 00:31:38.430
for themselves and their family.

00:31:38.430 --> 00:31:40.270
So my question for
you is what do you

00:31:40.270 --> 00:31:43.530
see as the biggest opportunity
for the Federal Government

00:31:43.530 --> 00:31:46.480
to help people who currently
are only living paycheck

00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:49.244
to paycheck to actually
be able to develop some

00:31:49.244 --> 00:31:51.160
of that equity for
themselves and their family

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:52.115
for the long term?

00:31:52.115 --> 00:31:54.615
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS: Well,
I think the Federal Government

00:31:54.615 --> 00:31:57.880
needs to do more to help people
that have been left and left

00:31:57.880 --> 00:31:59.340
behind.

00:31:59.340 --> 00:32:06.360
To make small loans available
with very low interest, maybe

00:32:06.360 --> 00:32:14.260
in some instances
probably not any interest.

00:32:14.260 --> 00:32:19.146
People just need a little help--
just need a helping hand--

00:32:19.146 --> 00:32:21.343
to help make people a
little more independent.

00:32:23.144 --> 00:32:24.060
We don't do it enough.

00:32:27.330 --> 00:32:33.140
We should see that every
child receive the best

00:32:33.140 --> 00:32:38.660
possible education, especially
in poor neighborhoods

00:32:38.660 --> 00:32:39.485
in rural America.

00:32:41.640 --> 00:32:44.710
That's why I've taken
such a strong stand

00:32:44.710 --> 00:32:47.370
for comprehensive
immigration reform.

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:51.830
To help people move
up, and the people

00:32:51.830 --> 00:32:58.530
will not live in a state
of want, a state of need.

00:33:00.210 --> 00:33:03.450
You know, we're one of
the wealthiest countries

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:09.330
on the planet, and we need
to use some of our resources

00:33:09.330 --> 00:33:14.720
to help and not continue
to make more bombs

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:15.650
and missiles and guns.

00:33:17.197 --> 00:33:18.030
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:33:21.699 --> 00:33:22.240
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:24.380
Thank you, Congressmen
and Andrew, for coming.

00:33:25.430 --> 00:33:27.970
I'm actually going to Ferguson
at the end of the week

00:33:27.970 --> 00:33:30.305
to support group there
called Amplify Ferguson.

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:35.690
It's a team of media people
who are using technology

00:33:35.690 --> 00:33:38.600
to give voices to the people
outside of this regular news

00:33:38.600 --> 00:33:42.410
cycle, now that no one's really
focusing on people in Ferguson.

00:33:42.410 --> 00:33:44.870
I'm helping with some
civic engagement workshops

00:33:44.870 --> 00:33:46.740
that they have on Saturday.

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:49.570
I, myself, and not trained
in civic engagement.

00:33:49.570 --> 00:33:51.720
I just was really
drawn to this cause.

00:33:51.720 --> 00:33:53.880
And so I'm wondering
from you all, what

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:57.570
do you think about communities
like Ferguson and Ferguson?

00:33:57.570 --> 00:34:00.120
What's missing there
in terms of how people

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:02.780
are using government
or getting involved?

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:05.300
Honestly, what would you
teach, if you were me,

00:34:05.300 --> 00:34:07.894
when I go there this weekend?

00:34:07.894 --> 00:34:09.810
And what you think is
most effective for youth

00:34:09.810 --> 00:34:12.320
versus adults in that community?

00:34:13.415 --> 00:34:15.540
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
Andrew may want to respond,

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:17.704
but I would say
prepare yourself.

00:34:19.300 --> 00:34:21.550
Before we've been on
any sit-in, the Freedom

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:26.080
Ride, the march from Selma to
Montgomery, the Mississippi

00:34:26.080 --> 00:34:28.120
Summer Project, we studied.

00:34:29.290 --> 00:34:31.280
And today there's all
type of literature.

00:34:33.670 --> 00:34:36.409
Watch "Eyes on the Prize."

00:34:36.409 --> 00:34:40.590
There's an NBC white paper that
came out many, many years ago,

00:34:40.590 --> 00:34:44.889
which the late Chad Huntley
narrated the white paper

00:34:44.889 --> 00:34:46.865
about the Nashville
sit-in story.

00:34:48.320 --> 00:34:51.310
And in the book you'll
see the do's and don'ts

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:55.245
Back then we didn't have
a website, Facebook.

00:34:57.419 --> 00:34:58.335
We didn't have Google.

00:35:00.567 --> 00:35:01.900
We need even have a fax machine.

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:05.865
We had the old
mimeograph machine.

00:35:05.865 --> 00:35:09.285
But we used what we
had to change America.

00:35:09.285 --> 00:35:10.285
You have to be creative.

00:35:13.660 --> 00:35:16.630
I think in Ferguson
people have got

00:35:16.630 --> 00:35:20.200
to become active in
the political process.

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:23.570
It doesn't make sense
that so few people get out

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:25.240
and vote there.

00:35:25.240 --> 00:35:29.490
As I've said many, many times
to my colleagues and to people

00:35:29.490 --> 00:35:33.040
all around the country
that the vote is powerful.

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:34.059
In this precious.

00:35:34.059 --> 00:35:34.850
It's almost sacred.

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:38.745
And we have to use it
to get things done.

00:35:39.910 --> 00:35:44.970
The more young people,
more minority, more women,

00:35:44.970 --> 00:35:48.840
get out and turn
out-- all of us just

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:54.880
turn out and show up and cast
a vote-- we can remake America,

00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:57.480
make it better for everybody.

00:36:01.420 --> 00:36:04.940
ANDREW AYDIN: I think
the most important thing

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:06.630
to keep in mind is
to look to our past

00:36:06.630 --> 00:36:07.920
and see what worked before.

00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:10.160
I think it would be very helpful
if many of the organizations

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:12.326
there modeled themselves
after the Nashville Student

00:36:12.326 --> 00:36:14.390
Movement, which was
largely believed

00:36:14.390 --> 00:36:16.950
to be the most
disciplined and orderly

00:36:16.950 --> 00:36:18.450
of the individual
student movements.

00:36:19.780 --> 00:36:21.180
Read Emerson.

00:36:21.180 --> 00:36:22.520
Read Thoreau.

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:23.290
Read Gandhi.

00:36:24.500 --> 00:36:26.940
Study nonviolence, because
the most important part

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:29.270
is the details.

00:36:29.270 --> 00:36:29.770
Right?

00:36:29.770 --> 00:36:31.320
Where is the
statement of demands?

00:36:32.417 --> 00:36:34.000
Before they left on
the Freedom Rides,

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.860
they mailed a specific letter
to the Attorney General,

00:36:36.860 --> 00:36:39.450
to the President and the press
with their specific demands

00:36:39.450 --> 00:36:40.991
for what they were
trying to achieve.

00:36:41.710 --> 00:36:42.210
Right?

00:36:42.210 --> 00:36:45.400
There is a way that
has worked in the past,

00:36:45.400 --> 00:36:47.860
and it's going to work again.

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:50.459
We just have to make sure that
everybody knows how to do it.

00:36:50.459 --> 00:36:51.750
That's why we're doing "March."

00:36:51.750 --> 00:36:54.375
That's why you should use Martin
Luther King and the Montgomery

00:36:54.375 --> 00:36:55.850
story or "March" or these tools.

00:36:55.850 --> 00:36:58.520
I mean, we're not
doing something

00:36:58.520 --> 00:37:00.240
that hasn't worked before.

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:04.331
And, as you look out there,
you see people who are thirsty.

00:37:04.331 --> 00:37:05.080
They want to know.

00:37:05.080 --> 00:37:06.646
They want to know
how do I do this?

00:37:06.646 --> 00:37:08.562
And we've just got to
get it into their hands.

00:37:09.732 --> 00:37:10.565
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

