00:51:36.570 --> 00:51:39.940
And put people in places
where they will speak up

00:51:39.940 --> 00:51:41.610
and speak out and organize.

00:51:41.610 --> 00:51:43.815
I've said it all
along that I think

00:51:43.815 --> 00:51:45.190
the America people
are too quiet.

00:51:46.580 --> 00:51:48.725
Just too quiet, too complacent.

00:51:50.700 --> 00:51:56.170
If this is 1960 or 1965, there
would be hundreds of thousands

00:51:56.170 --> 00:51:58.040
of people in the
streets of America.

00:51:59.540 --> 00:52:04.305
After the beating of us
in Selma on March 7, 1965,

00:52:04.305 --> 00:52:09.052
there were major demonstrations
in every major city in America,

00:52:09.052 --> 00:52:13.210
on 80 college
campuses, overnight.

00:52:14.781 --> 00:52:16.320
It happened on a Sunday.

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:18.030
By that Tuesday
people were sitting

00:52:18.030 --> 00:52:22.730
in the White House, the
Department of Justice.

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:26.430
Even the President said his
children couldn't sleep,

00:52:26.430 --> 00:52:28.060
his two daughters
couldn't sleep,

00:52:28.060 --> 00:52:30.298
because people were singing
"We Shall overcome."

00:52:32.290 --> 00:52:37.880
We have to get out there again
and push and pull and have

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:38.755
some created tension.

00:52:41.210 --> 00:52:43.609
So I-- you have to
go out and organize.

00:52:43.609 --> 00:52:44.150
I don't know.

00:52:44.150 --> 00:52:47.400
If we didn't have
what you have today,

00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:50.050
I don't know what we would
have been able to accomplish.

00:52:50.050 --> 00:52:54.440
We got to use these tools,
use these instruments,

00:52:54.440 --> 00:52:58.875
use the information,
to recreate America.

00:53:00.690 --> 00:53:01.960
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:53:05.304 --> 00:53:06.970
AUDIENCE: Congressman,
Andrew, thank you

00:53:06.970 --> 00:53:09.080
both for your life of service.

00:53:09.080 --> 00:53:10.060
My name is Seth Marvin.

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:11.690
I work here on the
Googlers Give Team.

00:53:11.690 --> 00:53:14.590
And we help employees volunteer,
and give away their money.

00:53:14.590 --> 00:53:17.972
And I used to work at
City Year, and I thank you

00:53:17.972 --> 00:53:18.680
for your service.

00:53:18.680 --> 00:53:20.660
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
I'm a City Year jacket.

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:20.930
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:53:20.930 --> 00:53:23.200
You're an incredible supporter
of City Year and National

00:53:23.200 --> 00:53:23.550
Service.

00:53:23.550 --> 00:53:24.520
So thank you for that.

00:53:26.090 --> 00:53:29.480
In the spirit of City
Year, we carried backpacks,

00:53:29.480 --> 00:53:30.504
we wore a uniform.

00:53:30.504 --> 00:53:31.170
And I'm curious.

00:53:31.170 --> 00:53:34.390
You mentioned the backpack
that you wore over the--

00:53:34.390 --> 00:53:35.715
in the March over the bridge.

00:53:35.715 --> 00:53:36.840
I've been over that bridge.

00:53:36.840 --> 00:53:39.077
It's amazing to sort of
walk in your footsteps

00:53:39.077 --> 00:53:40.910
and see what you've
been able to accomplish.

00:53:40.910 --> 00:53:41.840
But I'm curious.

00:53:41.840 --> 00:53:43.320
What would you put
in your backpack

00:53:43.320 --> 00:53:45.837
today if you're going
out to lead that march?

00:53:45.837 --> 00:53:47.920
And Andrew, for you, I'd
love to hear more about--

00:53:47.920 --> 00:53:48.780
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
What instruments would I

00:53:48.780 --> 00:53:50.890
have, Andrew, in that backpack?

00:53:50.890 --> 00:53:52.490
AUDIENCE: What would be in that?

00:53:52.490 --> 00:53:54.260
You mentioned an apple,
an orange, a couple books.

00:53:54.260 --> 00:53:55.690
What would be in
that backpack today?

00:53:55.690 --> 00:53:57.564
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
Well, you know, back,

00:53:57.564 --> 00:54:01.540
growing up the way I grew up,
we didn't have a telephone.

00:54:02.910 --> 00:54:05.670
We didn't have a subscription
to a newspaper we were so poor.

00:54:06.880 --> 00:54:09.800
But my grandfather had one.

00:54:09.800 --> 00:54:13.830
And each day when he would
finish reading his newspaper,

00:54:13.830 --> 00:54:16.890
we would get his
newspaper and read it.

00:54:16.890 --> 00:54:20.100
Some of our neighbors had,
what we called party line.

00:54:21.280 --> 00:54:23.234
I would have a telephone
in that backpack.

00:54:23.234 --> 00:54:24.525
I would be able to communicate.

00:54:26.220 --> 00:54:30.290
And probably have maybe a
small computer or something.

00:54:32.860 --> 00:54:36.270
And Andrew would teach
me all of the way.

00:54:38.484 --> 00:54:39.025
He's the man.

00:54:40.820 --> 00:54:43.330
Andrew what would you
advise me have in it?

00:54:44.539 --> 00:54:46.830
ANDREW AYDIN: I think you
just need a phone these days.

00:54:46.830 --> 00:54:47.060
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS: Yeah.

00:54:47.060 --> 00:54:47.760
Just a phone.

00:54:47.760 --> 00:54:49.260
ANDREW AYDIN: Can
start a revolution

00:54:49.260 --> 00:54:50.415
with this little device.

00:54:50.415 --> 00:54:52.290
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
But to be very frank,

00:54:52.290 --> 00:54:54.710
I wish I had the backpack back.

00:54:54.710 --> 00:54:57.444
People ask me all the time,
what happened to your backpack?

00:54:57.444 --> 00:54:58.860
What happened to
your trench coat?

00:55:01.080 --> 00:55:04.230
People from the Smithsonian,
from the Library of Congress.

00:55:04.230 --> 00:55:06.509
We don't know what
happened to it.

00:55:06.509 --> 00:55:08.300
AUDIENCE: And Andrew,
I'd love to hear more

00:55:08.300 --> 00:55:10.160
about the tools
that you mentioned,

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:12.260
Google Organize
and Google March.

00:55:12.260 --> 00:55:13.760
If you can answer
any more specifics

00:55:13.760 --> 00:55:15.040
on what those might look like.

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:16.750
What are we missing
at this point?

00:55:16.750 --> 00:55:19.326
ANDREW AYDIN: So, when
w get on social media,

00:55:19.326 --> 00:55:20.700
the message can
spread like that.

00:55:20.700 --> 00:55:23.440
We did the mug shot Tweet
a couple months ago,

00:55:23.440 --> 00:55:25.290
and it was like 50,000
re-Tweets, because we

00:55:25.290 --> 00:55:27.915
were so shocked that it
was only 53 years ago

00:55:27.915 --> 00:55:30.750
that somebody went to
Parchment Print Prison

00:55:30.750 --> 00:55:32.270
for using a white restroom.

00:55:33.660 --> 00:55:34.160
Right?

00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:37.900
These tools need to dramatize
these same struggles that

00:55:37.900 --> 00:55:38.950
are going on today.

00:55:40.210 --> 00:55:46.320
I think when we shine a bright
light-- the world light,

00:55:46.320 --> 00:55:50.950
if you will-- on to some
of these injustices,

00:55:50.950 --> 00:55:53.530
then people are much
more willing to act.

00:55:53.530 --> 00:55:56.830
But above all else, we've
got to get people to show up.

00:55:56.830 --> 00:55:58.510
We've got to find
a way to get people

00:55:58.510 --> 00:56:00.210
to let their presence
be their voice.

00:56:01.900 --> 00:56:03.800
We have a generation
now who's almost

00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:05.945
bordering on becoming
armchair activists.

00:56:07.030 --> 00:56:09.010
They post things and
they come complain

00:56:09.010 --> 00:56:11.174
that they think it's wrong,
but when it comes down

00:56:11.174 --> 00:56:12.590
to showing up and
putting pressure

00:56:12.590 --> 00:56:14.500
on your elected officials,
because let's be honest,

00:56:14.500 --> 00:56:16.666
most people in Congress
don't move without pressure.

00:56:17.602 --> 00:56:19.060
It's been that way
for a long time.

00:56:19.060 --> 00:56:20.309
It's not new to this Congress.

00:56:21.780 --> 00:56:23.040
You have too few John Lewis's.

00:56:24.780 --> 00:56:26.504
And so we have to get
people to show up.

00:56:26.504 --> 00:56:28.420
That was the point of
the March on Washington.

00:56:28.420 --> 00:56:30.119
And look how well it worked.

00:56:30.119 --> 00:56:31.910
Maybe it sparked a
backlash, but in the end

00:56:31.910 --> 00:56:34.270
it dramatized and helped
continue the efforts.

00:56:34.270 --> 00:56:37.020
More importantly, look at the
Mississippi Freedom Summer.

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:39.960
Schwerner, Chaney,
and Goodman died

00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:42.660
so that we could have a Civil
Rights Act and a Voting Rights

00:56:42.660 --> 00:56:43.680
Act.

00:56:43.680 --> 00:56:45.200
These people showed up.

00:56:45.200 --> 00:56:46.160
They went to schools.

00:56:46.160 --> 00:56:47.210
They educated themselves.

00:56:47.210 --> 00:56:48.480
They organized.

00:56:48.480 --> 00:56:51.320
So we have to make a
way to put these tools

00:56:51.320 --> 00:56:52.770
in the hands of everybody.

00:56:52.770 --> 00:56:55.780
First the lessons of
nonviolence, the history

00:56:55.780 --> 00:56:59.370
of nonviolence, how it was
used successfully, and then

00:56:59.370 --> 00:57:02.590
take it to that next step
and help people show up.

00:57:02.590 --> 00:57:03.835
Help people mobilize.

00:57:05.820 --> 00:57:09.820
It was just a few weeks ago that
we had a college student put

00:57:09.820 --> 00:57:13.960
out a Tweet with a hashtag that
garnered 3,000 people marching

00:57:13.960 --> 00:57:16.760
through the streets of
Atlanta in solidarity

00:57:16.760 --> 00:57:18.500
of Ferguson, including
Congressman Lewis.

00:57:18.500 --> 00:57:19.570
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
And so many people

00:57:19.570 --> 00:57:21.040
thought I was there.

00:57:21.040 --> 00:57:23.090
They thought I was at Ferguson.

00:57:23.090 --> 00:57:28.610
They saw me walking it in
the march, holding up my arm.

00:57:31.640 --> 00:57:32.350
But that's--

00:57:32.350 --> 00:57:33.305
ANDREW AYDIN: No.

00:57:33.305 --> 00:57:34.580
And getting people to show up.

00:57:34.580 --> 00:57:35.788
But I think also information.

00:57:37.100 --> 00:57:39.110
We don't understand
and we don't fully

00:57:39.110 --> 00:57:41.160
appreciate how much
governance actually

00:57:41.160 --> 00:57:42.840
happens at the local level.

00:57:42.840 --> 00:57:43.340
Right?

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:45.190
I mean, we're fighting
a fight right now

00:57:45.190 --> 00:57:47.570
to get people
registered to vote.

00:57:47.570 --> 00:57:50.800
And that's a local decision
first, at the county level

00:57:50.800 --> 00:57:52.430
and then at the state level.

00:57:52.430 --> 00:57:54.410
So how do you pressure
a Secretary of State

00:57:54.410 --> 00:57:57.100
to recognize valid
voter applications when

00:57:57.100 --> 00:57:59.764
they know that it will mean
that they will lose an election?

00:57:59.764 --> 00:58:01.680
How do you pressure your
county-wide officials

00:58:01.680 --> 00:58:04.340
to make it easier to
register and vote?

00:58:05.220 --> 00:58:05.720
Right?

00:58:05.720 --> 00:58:08.580
I mean we all vote on a Tuesday
and nobody gets the day off,

00:58:08.580 --> 00:58:10.730
and we say everybody has
the opportunity to vote.

00:58:10.730 --> 00:58:13.820
But the fact is that
most people have a job.

00:58:13.820 --> 00:58:15.520
And they're tired
when they get home.

00:58:15.520 --> 00:58:18.330
And they have to be into the
polling place by 7:00 o'clock.

00:58:18.330 --> 00:58:20.220
I never get home
by 7:00 o'clock.

00:58:20.220 --> 00:58:22.410
But Congressman
Lewis says take time.

00:58:22.410 --> 00:58:23.550
Go vote.

00:58:23.550 --> 00:58:24.330
Right?

00:58:24.330 --> 00:58:26.190
We should make it
a national holiday.

00:58:26.190 --> 00:58:28.690
We should press our Congress
to make it a national holiday.

00:58:28.690 --> 00:58:31.320
We should make voting as easy
as drinking a glass of water.

00:58:32.016 --> 00:58:32.515
Sorry.

00:58:32.515 --> 00:58:33.380
I stole your line.

00:58:33.380 --> 00:58:34.796
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: That's OK.

00:58:35.574 --> 00:58:36.840
That's OK.

00:58:36.840 --> 00:58:38.589
AUDIENCE: Thank you
both for your service.

00:58:38.589 --> 00:58:39.589
ANDREW AYDIN: Thank you.

00:58:43.380 --> 00:58:47.180
AUDIENCE: I either have
1,000 questions or none,

00:58:47.180 --> 00:58:49.020
but I wanted to say
thank you so much

00:58:49.020 --> 00:58:51.840
for what you've done for all
of us, because none of us

00:58:51.840 --> 00:58:53.730
are free unless we're all free.

00:58:53.730 --> 00:58:58.140
And I'm old enough-- I
was a young teenager when

00:58:58.140 --> 00:58:59.730
you were marching
on that bridge,

00:58:59.730 --> 00:59:01.462
and I remember seeing
the news stories

00:59:01.462 --> 00:59:02.670
and not really understanding.

00:59:04.130 --> 00:59:07.880
And just thank you very
much for your courage

00:59:07.880 --> 00:59:10.330
and all your efforts
on behalf of all of us.

00:59:10.330 --> 00:59:11.773
Thank you.

00:59:11.773 --> 00:59:15.140
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:19.470 --> 00:59:21.555
AUDIENCE: Thank you,
Congressman Lewis and Andrew.

00:59:23.190 --> 00:59:25.800
So one of the things, I
feel, of my generation

00:59:25.800 --> 00:59:27.300
is that we actually
feel the vote is

00:59:27.300 --> 00:59:30.440
a pretty ineffective tool
for getting our voices heard.

00:59:31.770 --> 00:59:35.230
And given that we're in Silicon
Valley where you see technology

00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:39.300
playing a role to do more than
just spreading information

00:59:39.300 --> 00:59:42.350
as in like being sort
of armchair activists

00:59:42.350 --> 00:59:46.200
and being able to play a role
despite having a full time

00:59:46.200 --> 00:59:51.390
job, what are the things you
think that, as technologists,

00:59:51.390 --> 00:59:53.459
we can all do to
create more impact?

00:59:53.459 --> 00:59:55.000
ANDREW AYDIN: Well,
I think it's time

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:57.650
for us to start the conversation
about online voting,

00:59:57.650 --> 01:00:01.250
online voter registration,
and making it national idea.

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:08.420
It's oftentimes antiquated
rules with a cumbersome way

01:00:08.420 --> 01:00:11.190
of doing it to get
people to show up.

01:00:11.190 --> 01:00:12.930
And we make it too hard.

01:00:12.930 --> 01:00:14.120
We have all this technology.

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:17.470
We should find new ways to
use it in the voting process.

01:00:17.470 --> 01:00:20.320
It can be secure if
we work hard enough.

01:00:20.320 --> 01:00:24.960
If Diebold can advocate
for using electronic voting

01:00:24.960 --> 01:00:28.510
machines in their
election, then perhaps it's

01:00:28.510 --> 01:00:33.310
time for us to look
at it for everybody

01:00:33.310 --> 01:00:35.832
online as opposed to
just the touch screens,

01:00:35.832 --> 01:00:37.790
because there was so much
controversy with that

01:00:37.790 --> 01:00:38.748
that they supported it.

01:00:38.748 --> 01:00:40.770
But I think there's
a flip side of that.

01:00:40.770 --> 01:00:42.696
We can't advocate
that until everybody

01:00:42.696 --> 01:00:43.820
has access to the internet.

01:00:45.014 --> 01:00:46.430
I think it's time
for us to call--

01:00:46.430 --> 01:00:48.260
are you familiar with
the lifeline program?

01:00:48.260 --> 01:00:48.650
AUDIENCE: No.

01:00:48.650 --> 01:00:50.358
ANDREW AYDIN: It's
something the FCC does

01:00:50.358 --> 01:00:53.600
so that folks who live
below the poverty line

01:00:53.600 --> 01:00:55.390
can have access to a cellphone.

01:00:55.390 --> 01:00:55.930
Right?

01:00:55.930 --> 01:00:59.750
I think we need to expand
that to include data

01:00:59.750 --> 01:01:02.190
so that everybody can have
access to information.

01:01:02.190 --> 01:01:05.300
If you're poor, if you're
under the poverty line,

01:01:05.300 --> 01:01:06.950
you just get a phone
with data on it.

01:01:07.960 --> 01:01:09.820
That's how people get
their information.

01:01:09.820 --> 01:01:11.570
How are we expecting
people to be informed

01:01:11.570 --> 01:01:13.650
if we don't give them
the tools to be informed?

01:01:13.650 --> 01:01:16.220
We're cutting library budgets
at a record pace, which

01:01:16.220 --> 01:01:17.720
used to be the only
place they could

01:01:17.720 --> 01:01:19.240
get free access to the internet.

01:01:19.240 --> 01:01:20.990
So we're going to take
it away from there.

01:01:20.990 --> 01:01:23.630
We've got to push to give
it to them somewhere else.

01:01:23.630 --> 01:01:25.650
And, I think, part
of it, too, is

01:01:25.650 --> 01:01:28.750
that you're not going to
fix everything in a day.

01:01:28.750 --> 01:01:31.480
And we're going to have to find
small things to build momentum.

01:01:32.620 --> 01:01:34.729
So if it's expanding
the lifeline program

01:01:34.729 --> 01:01:37.020
to include data for folks
living under the poverty line

01:01:37.020 --> 01:01:41.780
and giving everybody access to
a phone with data, so be it.

01:01:41.780 --> 01:01:43.430
It's better to spend
our money on that

01:01:43.430 --> 01:01:44.513
than to spend it on bombs.

01:01:45.602 --> 01:01:47.260
AUDIENCE: I think
all of us can agree.

01:01:47.260 --> 01:01:48.330
ANDREW AYDIN: Yeah.

01:01:48.330 --> 01:01:49.250
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:01:52.940 --> 01:01:56.120
AUDIENCE: Thank you, Congressman
Lewis, for coming, and Andrew.

01:01:56.120 --> 01:01:59.640
My question is about
truth and reconciliation.

01:02:01.760 --> 01:02:04.820
I know that a lot
of the problems

01:02:04.820 --> 01:02:06.560
here are between
different people

01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:09.130
having-- they have different,
conflicting views about what

01:02:09.130 --> 01:02:10.220
really happened.

01:02:10.220 --> 01:02:13.010
And I think that people are
afraid to step forward and say

01:02:13.010 --> 01:02:15.730
what happened in the '60s, what
happened with the lynchings,

01:02:15.730 --> 01:02:20.860
and so there's this distrust
that kind of continues on.

01:02:22.260 --> 01:02:24.080
So what are your
thoughts about that?

01:02:24.080 --> 01:02:28.360
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: I believe deeply

01:02:28.360 --> 01:02:31.560
that's why we must move as
a people and as a nation.

01:02:32.770 --> 01:02:34.800
There's still a lot
of hurt and pain.

01:02:36.460 --> 01:02:41.150
I know individuals in
African American community.

01:02:41.150 --> 01:02:45.760
The book came about
lynching, a small book.

01:02:45.760 --> 01:02:49.220
It was an exhibit in
different parts of America.

01:02:50.850 --> 01:02:54.350
People I know in African
American community

01:02:54.350 --> 01:03:00.520
couldn't go to the museum or
to a church or to the school.

01:03:00.520 --> 01:03:03.490
And there was some colleges
and universities in this South

01:03:03.490 --> 01:03:05.600
were afraid to display it.

01:03:05.600 --> 01:03:08.230
They thought something
would happen.

01:03:08.230 --> 01:03:09.900
But we need to face the truth.

01:03:09.900 --> 01:03:10.750
It did happen.

01:03:12.160 --> 01:03:13.780
It did happen.

01:03:13.780 --> 01:03:15.580
So you cannot hide it.

01:03:15.580 --> 01:03:16.880
Face it.

01:03:16.880 --> 01:03:19.890
And I think South
Africa has one up on us.

01:03:21.240 --> 01:03:26.175
They did a better job of
bringing people together.

01:03:26.665 --> 01:03:28.040
And that's what
we've been trying

01:03:28.040 --> 01:03:31.600
to do on a limited basis in
parts of the American South,

01:03:31.600 --> 01:03:34.125
in Alabama, when we
go back to Montgomery

01:03:34.125 --> 01:03:36.760
and to Selma and to Birmingham.

01:03:36.760 --> 01:03:42.700
Let people-- the people
that was on the other side,

01:03:42.700 --> 01:03:45.770
black and white-- let
them come together.

01:03:45.770 --> 01:03:48.595
I've gone back to Birmingham
on some of these trips,

01:03:48.595 --> 01:03:51.540
and on one occasion
when I was back there,

01:03:51.540 --> 01:03:55.960
a white gentleman
said, middle-aged,

01:03:55.960 --> 01:03:57.610
said I want to
speak to John Lewis.

01:03:59.750 --> 01:04:02.680
And someone said
he's right here.

01:04:02.680 --> 01:04:06.350
And he said, Mr. Lewis, I
want to apologize to you

01:04:06.350 --> 01:04:08.935
on behalf of all of the
white people of Alabama

01:04:08.935 --> 01:04:09.984
for what we did.

01:04:12.454 --> 01:04:14.770
We need to get there.

01:04:14.770 --> 01:04:16.610
People in the
Congress, we're afraid.

01:04:16.610 --> 01:04:18.155
We're afraid to
issue an apology.

01:04:19.800 --> 01:04:23.450
The Congress, the National
Assembly of the United States

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:28.972
of America is afraid to say
we're sorry for slavery,

01:04:28.972 --> 01:04:31.540
we're sorry for the
system of segregation

01:04:31.540 --> 01:04:32.780
and racial discrimination.

01:04:32.780 --> 01:04:36.060
So that legacy is still there.

01:04:36.060 --> 01:04:37.103
It lingers.

01:04:37.103 --> 01:04:40.047
AUDIENCE: And how it affects
today and what's going on today

01:04:40.047 --> 01:04:40.880
and how it connects.

01:04:40.880 --> 01:04:42.296
I think a lot of
people don't make

01:04:42.296 --> 01:04:48.340
that connection between slavery,
racism, post-reconstruction,

01:04:48.340 --> 01:04:50.955
and what's happening in our
cities today, and Ferguson.

01:04:52.122 --> 01:04:54.080
I think people just don't
make that connection.

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:55.922
Also, I want to say
that there's definitely

01:04:55.922 --> 01:04:58.130
people who are willing to
stand up because, you know,

01:04:58.130 --> 01:04:59.950
Occupy was amazing.

01:04:59.950 --> 01:05:01.780
I was totally blown
away that they

01:05:01.780 --> 01:05:04.350
were able to get so many people
together across the city.

01:05:04.350 --> 01:05:08.890
I think they probably lacked a
message or a concrete message.

01:05:08.890 --> 01:05:11.180
And also, I just want
to say thank you.

01:05:11.180 --> 01:05:13.270
I know I wouldn't be here
if it wasn't for you.

01:05:13.270 --> 01:05:13.890
So thank you.

01:05:13.890 --> 01:05:15.306
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: Thank you.

01:05:15.306 --> 01:05:18.460
There's an exhibit at
the Library of Congress.

01:05:18.460 --> 01:05:23.185
It should continue until
next September of '15.

01:05:24.710 --> 01:05:26.770
Unreal, unbelievable.

01:05:26.770 --> 01:05:28.650
So it may travel.

01:05:28.650 --> 01:05:33.260
But it's a complete history
of the whole struggle

01:05:33.260 --> 01:05:34.755
from the days of slavery.

01:05:34.755 --> 01:05:36.088
AUDIENCE: I'll have to catch it.

01:05:36.088 --> 01:05:36.640
Thank you.

01:05:36.640 --> 01:05:38.056
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: Thank you.

01:05:41.008 --> 01:05:42.990
AUDIENCE: Hello,
Congressman Lewis.

01:05:42.990 --> 01:05:47.520
You've talked a lot about
low voter participation

01:05:47.520 --> 01:05:48.220
and turnouts.

01:05:48.220 --> 01:05:51.120
And I feel like there have been
a lot of deliberate attempts

01:05:51.120 --> 01:05:53.930
to breed cynicism
and the feeling

01:05:53.930 --> 01:05:56.010
that our vote doesn't
matter, particularly

01:05:56.010 --> 01:05:59.040
for people who are more
likely to support equality.

01:06:00.410 --> 01:06:03.470
And one of the ways
that I've seen this done

01:06:03.470 --> 01:06:06.620
is by splitting up elections.

01:06:06.620 --> 01:06:08.420
Like, I remember
a conversation I

01:06:08.420 --> 01:06:10.520
had with a Republican
strategist once

01:06:10.520 --> 01:06:12.990
who talked about the
deliberate strategy

01:06:12.990 --> 01:06:15.290
to hold special elections
and things like that,

01:06:15.290 --> 01:06:18.380
because there's lower voter
turnouts in those elections,

01:06:18.380 --> 01:06:23.660
and those people about tend to
skew older and skew wealthier

01:06:23.660 --> 01:06:25.920
and skew more Republican.

01:06:25.920 --> 01:06:29.800
And even in a lot
of local elections

01:06:29.800 --> 01:06:32.670
are held at weird off times.

01:06:32.670 --> 01:06:35.610
And I've missed more
than one election

01:06:35.610 --> 01:06:37.260
when I moved to a
new city because it

01:06:37.260 --> 01:06:40.460
was like there was nothing
in any of the media

01:06:40.460 --> 01:06:43.420
that I get that let me know
that the election happened

01:06:43.420 --> 01:06:47.800
until there was a news story
three days later about who won.

01:06:47.800 --> 01:06:50.780
And even when I have
voted sometimes,

01:06:50.780 --> 01:06:55.730
by the time you get down
to family court judge,

01:06:55.730 --> 01:06:59.620
my question is why is this even
an elected position, much less

01:06:59.620 --> 01:07:03.020
having a sense of who would
be the better candidate here.

01:07:03.020 --> 01:07:06.060
So my question
is, what can we do

01:07:06.060 --> 01:07:09.890
to counteract the
forces that want

01:07:09.890 --> 01:07:13.100
to discourage voter turnout
through spreading out

01:07:13.100 --> 01:07:17.860
elections, and to help
it be easier for people

01:07:17.860 --> 01:07:19.800
to become informed voters?

01:07:19.890 --> 01:07:21.390
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: I think it's

01:07:21.390 --> 01:07:27.560
important for local partisan
or nonpartisan organizations

01:07:27.560 --> 01:07:31.460
and groups, like the League of
Women Voters, good government

01:07:31.460 --> 01:07:38.570
groups, to lobby, to organize
and get legislation passed,

01:07:38.570 --> 01:07:42.400
to change the type of voting.

01:07:44.450 --> 01:07:48.620
But my philosophies
are also that you

01:07:48.620 --> 01:07:51.970
should vote in every election,
even if it's only the dog

01:07:51.970 --> 01:07:54.527
catcher, you want to
vote for the dog catcher

01:07:54.527 --> 01:07:55.860
or vote against the dog catcher.

01:07:56.890 --> 01:07:58.050
But vote.

01:07:58.050 --> 01:07:59.422
It's just that important.

01:07:59.422 --> 01:08:00.880
In our young people,
we have to get

01:08:00.880 --> 01:08:03.970
people in the habit
of participating,

01:08:03.970 --> 01:08:08.061
minorities in the South,
in the habit of voting,

01:08:08.061 --> 01:08:09.310
in the habit of participating.

01:08:11.339 --> 01:08:12.880
And we should take
our young children

01:08:12.880 --> 01:08:13.890
when we go to the polls.

01:08:15.440 --> 01:08:18.970
Take them to the polls with
us and let them punch and do

01:08:18.970 --> 01:08:22.720
whatever you do
so they can see it

01:08:22.720 --> 01:08:25.015
become a part of
their existence.

01:08:27.987 --> 01:08:28.820
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:08:28.820 --> 01:08:30.236
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: Thank you.

01:08:32.199 --> 01:08:32.740
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:08:32.740 --> 01:08:35.500
This may be a bit more of a
statement than a question.

01:08:35.500 --> 01:08:39.220
First off, I wanted to say that
I'm a very recent Californian,

01:08:39.220 --> 01:08:41.060
having here moved
here two years ago,

01:08:41.060 --> 01:08:44.399
and spent the preceding
20 years in Atlanta,

01:08:44.399 --> 01:08:47.130
and was extremely proud to
have had you as my Congressman

01:08:47.130 --> 01:08:49.662
for a great, great
deal of that time.

01:08:49.662 --> 01:08:51.120
CONGRESSMAN JOHN
LEWIS: Well, I try

01:08:51.120 --> 01:08:53.640
to do my best as a
member of Congress.

01:08:53.640 --> 01:08:56.250
This young man here said I've
been here since he was three.

01:08:58.550 --> 01:09:00.359
AUDIENCE: And I
wanted to thank you

01:09:00.359 --> 01:09:03.540
all for drawing the
sort of line of history,

01:09:03.540 --> 01:09:06.670
because well, my wife
is older than I am

01:09:06.670 --> 01:09:10.319
and she was involved in the
Vietnam Movement and protests

01:09:10.319 --> 01:09:11.100
against Vietnam.

01:09:12.120 --> 01:09:16.534
My father-- we lived in Texas,
and he sat at lunch counters.

01:09:17.970 --> 01:09:21.130
But one of my great honors
as part of the continuing

01:09:21.130 --> 01:09:25.034
movement, I personally met my
wife protesting US involvement

01:09:25.034 --> 01:09:29.510
in Central America
in the '80s was

01:09:29.510 --> 01:09:33.109
to be able to meet
representative of the Abraham

01:09:33.109 --> 01:09:36.590
Lincoln brigades from
the Spanish Civil War.

01:09:36.590 --> 01:09:40.939
And I was made acutely
aware of the legacy

01:09:40.939 --> 01:09:43.420
of the movements of the '30s.

01:09:43.420 --> 01:09:47.000
And so, it's a
continuous movement,

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:50.740
and I'm proud to be part
of this river in some form.

01:09:50.740 --> 01:09:54.860
And I'm very honored
to meet a giant.

01:09:54.860 --> 01:09:57.599
In that said, thank you.

01:09:57.599 --> 01:09:59.640
CONGRESSMAN JOHN LEWIS:
Thank you very much, sir.

01:09:59.640 --> 01:10:00.620
Thank you.

01:10:00.620 --> 01:10:02.090
Thank you.

